Apartment Description

Beautiful, modern, and extremely cozy two-room apartment for rent. It is located in the quiet Saska Kƒôpa area on Arabska Street 6, on the 3rd floor. Ideal for those who appreciate comfort, convenience, and a peaceful place to live, yet want to live close to the city center.

My friend and I rented the apartment together, but due to personal reasons, we have to move out.
Therefore, we are looking for new, responsible tenants to take our place - preferably a couple or people who will rent the apartment together.

The apartment is furnished and renovated in a modern style. It consists of two lockable rooms, a kitchen, a bathroom, a toilet, and a hallway.

The first room is spacious, has a large balcony. The room has a new, foldable sofa and spacious furniture in which you can store many things.
The second room is slightly smaller but equally cozy. Inside there is a comfortable foldable sofa and furniture providing plenty of storage space.
The kitchen is fully equipped: numerous cabinets, a washing machine, a dishwasher, a large refrigerator with a freezer.
The bathroom is modern and functional - there is a shower, toilet, sink, and space for small items.
The hallway has a large wardrobe for outerwear and other things and a beautiful mirror with ambient lighting.
The apartment maintains a comfortable temperature all year round - it is not hot in the summer, and pleasantly warm in the winter.

The apartment owners are friendly and kind people who will happily welcome responsible tenants.

Rent cost: 3300 PLN + utilities.
Deposit: 4000 PLN.

You won't regret choosing this apartment!

Feel free to contact us at: 513 042 227 (or via Telegram)

the apartment is available from January 1 ü§ó

What financial support can Ukrainians expect in 2024-2025?
Let's figure it out!
What social benefits are there for children?

Can I receive a one-time cash benefit (300 zloty)?
No. The one-time cash assistance for newcomers (300 zlotys) was canceled from July 1, 2024.
How to get help? Important details

‚úîÔ∏è To apply for social benefits, you need to obtain a PESEL number. ‚úîÔ∏è Some types of benefits and allowances can only be transferred to a bank account. They can also be arranged via a banking app or webpage. ‚úîÔ∏è There is also a "trusted profile" (Profil Zaufany) ‚Äì a free electronic tool for confirming your identity online and certifying documents. This can help in receiving benefits or resolving other formal issues. ‚úîÔ∏è More details:
Is it necessary to give up social assistance in Ukraine?

Yes, if you receive social assistance in Ukraine, it may affect your eligibility for aid in Poland (e.g., caregiver's allowance). To receive payments in Poland, you need to provide documents confirming the refusal of assistance in Ukraine. ‚úîÔ∏è Instructions on refusal:

With men (oni) ‚Äî if there is at least one man: "we did" ‚Äî robili≈õmy; "you did" ‚Äî robili≈õcie; "they did" ‚Äî robili. üìå And tables with all endings for the past tense can be found online or in textbooks. A few days ago, I learned about my brother's injury. Thank God he's alive. And do you know what he answered when asked: 'How are you? How can we help? What do you need?' I'm quoting now: 'I'm okay. I need a thermal sight and a mount with a Picatinny/Weaver rail, if there's any way to gather it or access to volunteers, it wouldn't be bad.'

A person who has been evacuated to the hospital and is waiting for surgery is thinking about the fact that he doesn't have a sight. In the photo, there's what remains of the previous one.

We are raising funds for a thermal sight for the 162 OBTR position. The sight allows for firing accurately in conditions of limited visibility (night, smoke, snow). After all, the occupiers almost always use smoke for assaults on our positions.

I ask you to support our defender!

Hello, dear all! I've asked before, but.. maybe someone can advise now: Is it mandatory to purchase an insurance policy for crossing the Ukrainian-Polish border for the purpose of transit, not tourism? Thank you! P.S. On January 10 I will be leaving Kyiv for Warsaw (expected arrival time in the morning of the 11th) and I can take some package with me.
If you do not have documents that provide health insurance for the EU, then you need to
I do not live in the EU, my goal is to get to the airport (and 1-2 days in Warsaw). And the country I'm flying to does not require an insurance policy.
Does it change anything? If you do not have documents that provide EU health insurance, then you need to buy insurance.
I don't know if it changes anything, that's why I specified the info more.
At the border, the Poles don't ask, if that's what you're interested in. But for your own safety, it is recommended, although you probably already know that üòâ
Yes, I am interested in crossing the border. Thank you)
Hello! Have they not been asking for a long time? Is it since the start of martial law in Ukraine?
How is it that they don't ask? They also demand it in printed form. I didn't have it printed, so they wanted to issue a fine, and it's big there.
Well, kind of, I agree, they always required it! Of course, unless you showed documents from any of the EU countries.
Hello everyone. Does anyone know how the offices will work in a week, during the Christmas week?
Nothing like that was asked 3 months ago.
Please tell me: did you show your Polish documents when crossing the border?
Yes, I showed it. In the compartment, there were also people who didn't have documents, no one asked for a policy.

Then the question is: is it a human factor or is there already some regulation that allows Ukrainians to enter the Schengen area without a medical policy? If there are no new regulatory documents, it might just be a human factor and it's up to luck: they may ask/may not ask.

Most answer that they are fleeing from the war, and then the questions disappear. By law, insurance is necessary, it is also better to travel with insurance than later, god forbid, to spend exorbitant amounts. Especially since insurance is not so expensive and costs

There are no such documents. The neighbor's son did not manage to arrange insurance in Slovakia - appendicitis- surgery- 4000 euros from the parents, the boy is a student. There was no shelter anymore, and there was no insurance yet. I think that's how it works in Poland too.

By the way, personally, before the war, no one ever asked for my insurance, only the green card.
But this does not mean that it's worth the risk))

And no one asked anything at the border))) so basically one's own health is purely one's own responsibility.
Good evening, please share your experience, has anyone brought a car from the USAüá∫üá∏ and cleared it through customs in Plüáµüá± for further use?

Well, I wrote from the experience of my relatives and acquaintances who either came or were passing through in the last six months. Maybe you have a different experience. But since there is such a lively discussion here, I didn't hesitate and read the info on the official website. I am attaching the link. In short, for a short stay, confirmation of medical insurance is not required (unless I read it poorly ;) And then let everyone make their own decision.
Wrote above

Yes, the question is interesting. A little more: In the legislative acts of the European Union, the issue of having an insurance policy is not explicitly stated. The EU Visa Code requires a medical insurance policy, but the border code does not include it in the list of mandatory documents. Also, among the reasons why border guards can refuse entry, the absence of an insurance policy with the tourist is not provided. However!!! A list of circumstances has been approved when having an insurance policy is mandatory: 1. If you are traveling in your own car - you must have a "Green Card" policy for third-party liability insurance for the car owner. 2. If extreme recreation is planned (this also includes vacationing at ski resorts). 3. When purchasing a travel package from tour operators, insurance with minimum coverage is included based on the law of Ukraine "On Tourism". 4. During travels with children. 5. When traveling for work or study.
Mandatory "when traveling with children"
Thank you all very much!!!
Thank you

text_entities.TRANSLATED_TEXT: Main types of payments: ‚Äî Support allowance for adults (≈öwiadczenie wspierajƒÖce). ‚Äî Allowance for children with disabilities (≈öwiadczenie pielƒôgnacyjne). ‚Äî One-time Za ≈ªyciem grant for newborns with prenatal disabilities. ‚Äî Monthly care allowance (Zasi≈Çek pielƒôgnacyjny) ‚Äî for those who care for a person over 75 years old or a person with confirmed disabilities. ‚Äî Special care allowance (Specjalny zasi≈Çek opieku≈Ñczy). ‚úÖ More details:
How to confirm disability?
The process of regaining status will take some time, but people who have legalized their stay in the country will be able to receive necessary treatment and rely on benefits:
Can guardianship be arranged?
Yes, blood relatives can arrange guardianship of a person with a disability. For consultations, contact the State Fund for Rehabilitation of Persons with Disabilities (PFRON).
I have a disability, and I need help paying for medical and assistive devices. Who can I call?
The State Fund for the Rehabilitation of Disabled Persons (PFRON) has launched the program 'Assistance to Citizens of Ukraine with Disabilities':

The program offers financial support for the purchase or repair of medical/assistive devices (e.g., prosthetics, wheelchairs, canes, crutches, catheters, etc.) upon request and as prescribed by a doctor, nurse, midwife, physiotherapist, or other authorized persons.
Can I refuse social assistance from Ukraine?

Yes. To be eligible for assistance (for example, zasi≈Çek pielƒôgnacyjny or ≈õwiadczenie pielƒôgnacyjne), applicants must provide documents confirming that they are not receiving these benefits in Ukraine. ‚úÖ Detailed information:
You can also contact the Contact Center of the Embassy of Ukraine in Poland at the numbers: +48 574 702 685, +48 754 703 414, +48 574 707 627, +48 574 711 813, or +48 (22) 621 39 79.
Can I access free medical care?

‚úÖ Yes. Poland provides free access to the healthcare system for Ukrainian citizens who arrived after February 24, 2022, under the same conditions as Polish citizens. You should bring your passport with a stamp or a similar document confirming your entry into Poland, or a PESEL number.
üìû Useful contacts:
Cancer patients can receive support from Fundacja Alivia: 48 22 266 03 40, onko_ukraine@alivia.org.p - Maps of places in Poland that support people with disabilities:
- National Health Fund Health Hotline (24/7): 800 190 590 - Information and Coordination Center for People with Disabilities: Tel.: +48 661 439 072 Email:

Association "Mudita" (Stowarzyszenie Mudita) (Krakow): support for people with disabilities and their families, information provision, support groups for caregivers, assistance with finding housing, help in obtaining specialized equipment, such as wheelchairs, etc.). Tel.: 539 866 471

‚ùóÔ∏èFor detailed information on social protection in Poland, visit the local Social Support Center (OPS).

What do you need to know about pension provision for Ukrainians in Poland?
Frequently asked questions.
I am a citizen of Ukraine of retirement age. Can I expect assistance?
Yes, if you are in Poland and have reached retirement age there or previously received a pension in Ukraine, you can receive your pension remotely.
Is there any additional assistance?

Yes, in Poland there is assistance for lonely people who cannot live independently and have documentary evidence of this status. Such people can receive 500 zlotys of assistance. However, only if the income from all benefits does not exceed 2157.08 zlotys. There is also a 'Neighborly Help' program, under which people over 60 years old, who have no relatives, can receive assistance for a person or organization that will help them with solving everyday issues. For example, if it is necessary to buy groceries, cook something, clean, repair, etc. The amount of assistance for each individual elderly person is determined by the gmina. To receive the payment, contact the gmina at your place of residence. More details:
üëâ
I am a citizen of Ukraine. How can I arrange a pension while staying in Poland?
You can apply for a pension through your personal account on the portal of the Pension Fund of Ukraine
or through the Polish Social Insurance Institution (ZUS).
Can you help me with applying for a pension?
You can apply for a pension through the portal of the Pension Fund of Ukraine or through the Polish Social Insurance Institution (ZUS). Step-by-step instructions:
üëâ
How can I open a bank account for receiving pension and financial aid payments while in Poland?

Opening a bank account and payment card can be done through the official website of an authorized Ukrainian bank or mobile application without physically visiting the bank branch. In this case, when opening an account, the bank identifies the client via video conference. 

With an open account, you will be able to submit an application for the payment (and/or change of payment method) of a pension or financial assistance through your bank electronically using a qualified electronic signature (QES).

Good day, community. I am trying to figure out the issue of further legal stay in Poland. I crossed the Polish border on September 15 and was on business in Europe, then returned back to Warsaw in October and flew to Turkey for 39 days, returned on December 7. A week after returning in December, I went to the office in Mokotow, where I was denied the status because I had already left the EU. Then I went to another office and was told the same thing. I asked how to extend my stay in Poland legally after 90 days, and they told me that I could stay in Poland until September or apply for a temporary residence. My 90 days will formally expire on January 21, and I am now thinking about whether to search for long-term housing and then provide the contract together with the form to the office. I understand that this will be when my 90 days expire. Is it worth applying for temporary registration so that in the event of a possible departure from Poland outside the EU in the spring, I won't have any problems? Or can I stay until September 2025 in Poland, exceeding the 90-day period?

Now the status of Ukrainian refugees is processed very quickly after crossing the border, so it is not surprising that you were refused. Ukrainians can legally stay in Poland until September 30, 2025 (the period for which temporary protection is provided), but it can still be extended. The problem is that you can stay in Poland, but if you leave, it's not certain that you'll be able to get back, as the 90 days in the Schengen area will expire. Also, you will not be able to confirm your legal stay in other Schengen countries if you encounter a random passport check.
For such money and such a time, anything but crime?
